50|$|In 1994 the National Institute of Corrections {{said that}} American <b>prison</b> <b>systems</b> did not {{adequately}} provide gynecological services. During that year {{half of the}} state <b>prison</b> <b>systems</b> surveyed by the institute provided female-specific health care services, including mammograms and pap smears. Amnesty International said that, in the systems offering those services, many women encountered long waiting lists. The results of study conducted in a Rhode Island prison indicated high levels of reproductive health risks (STDs, unplanned pregnancies, etc.), from which researchers concluded that providing reproductive health services to incarcerated women would be beneficial to the women, the community, and the criminal justice system.|$|R
